title: Sushi
description: Japanese dish consisting of cooked vinegared rice combined with other ingredients, usually seafood (often raw), vegetables, and occasionally tropical fruits.

title: Nasi Goreng
description: Indonesian style fried rice, typically flavored with sweet soy sauce (kecap manis), shallots, garlic, tamarind, chili, and accompanied by various additions like egg, chicken, shrimp, or vegetables.

title: Ramen
description: Japanese noodle soup dish consisting of wheat noodles served in a meat or fish-based broth, often flavored with soy sauce or miso, and topped with ingredients like sliced pork, nori, menma, and scallions.

title: Burger (Hamburger)
description: A food consisting of fillings—usually a patty of ground meat, typically beef—placed inside a sliced bun. Often served with cheese, lettuce, tomato, onion, pickles, bacon, or chiles.

title: Bebek Peking (Peking Duck)
description: Famous duck dish from Beijing that has been prepared since the imperial era. The duck is prized for its thin, crisp skin, with authentic versions serving mostly the skin and little meat.

title: Pizza
description: Italian dish consisting of a usually round, flat base of leavened wheat-based dough topped with tomatoes, cheese, and often various other ingredients, baked at a high temperature.

title: Rendang
description: Slow-cooked beef simmered in rich coconut milk and a mixture of spices, originating from West Sumatra. Often cited as one of the world's most delicious foods.

title: Sate (Satay)
description: Grilled skewers of seasoned meat (chicken, beef, lamb, etc.), served with a flavorful peanut sauce or kecap manis based sauce.

title: Tom Yum
description: Thai hot and sour soup, usually cooked with shrimp (Tom Yum Goong). Characterized by its distinct hot and sour flavors, with fragrant spices and herbs generously used in the broth.

title: Pad Thai
description: Stir-fried rice noodle dish commonly served as a street food and at casual local eateries in Thailand. Made with rice noodles, shrimp or chicken or tofu, peanuts, scrambled egg, and bean sprouts.
